x4freetext: The experiment was carried out at the
WNR facility at Los Alamos National Laboratory.
239Pu was placed inside
fission chamber. Total of 47 mg of 239Pu was arranged
in 22 deposits on every cathode of the fission
chamber. Diameter of each deposit was 33 mm.
Fission fragments are detected in a multilayer
fission chamber containing a stack of axial
ionization cells. 11 cathodes with fissile deposits
are on ground potential. Anode gap was 2.5 mm. The
chamber was filled with CF4 gas to ensure a fast
charge collection and operates 100 mbar above the
local atmospheric pressure. A time resolution better
than 0.8ns full width at half maximum could be
achieved.
Prompt fission neutrons were detected using
Chi-Nu high energy neutron detector array. The array
consists of 54 EJ-309 liquid scintillator detectors,
read by photomultipliers, and arranged on a
hemisphere with inner radius of about 1m around the
fission chamber. Diameter of each detector was 17.78
cm and thickness 5.08 cm. The detectors are placed at
nine different angles, with six detectors per angle,
theta(lab) ranging from 30 deg to 150 deg, with
respect to the beam axis. A 2 mm thick Pb shield was
placed in front of each detector to reduce the amount
of low energy gamma rays. Pulse shape discrimination
technique was used to distinguish neutrons and gamma
rays. The whole array covers close to 10% of 4Pi
solid angle.
Primary as well as secondary neutron energy was
determined by time of flight. Proton beam consist of
625 mu-s long macropulses with repetition rate of
100 Hz. Each macropulse is composed of series of 250 ps
wide micropulses separated by 1.8 mu-s. A 1.27-cm thick
polyethylene absorber was placed into the beam line to
harden the spectra and reduce the wraparound effect.
Fission detector was placed at a distance 20 m from
the spallation target.
A white pulsed neutron beam was produced by
spallation of thick tungsten target by 800 MeV pulsed
proton beam.
